revision.text:
{{Politics of Latvia}}
The '''Agudas Israel''' ([[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] for "Union of Israel") was a political party in [[Latvia]] in the inter-war period. Primarily a party of the [[orthodox Judaism|orthodox Jews]], it was the most conservative of the Jewish parties in the country, seeking to limit the power of state monopolies. It was led by [[Mordehai Dubin]].<ref>Vincent E McHale (1983) ''Political parties of Europe'', Greenwood Press, p448 {{ISBN|0-313-23804-9}}</ref>
==History== The party first contested national elections in [[Latvian parliamentary election, 1922|1922]], when it won two seats in the [[1st Saeima]].<ref name=NS>[[Dieter Nohlen]] & Philip Stöver (2010) ''Elections in Europe: A data handbook'', p1143 {{ISBN|978-3-8329-5609-7}}</ref> It retained both seats in the [[2nd Saeima]] after the [[Latvian parliamentary election, 1925|1925 elections]], but was reduced to one seat in the [[Latvian parliamentary election, 1928|1928 elections]]. The [[Latvian parliamentary election, 1931|1931 elections]] saw the party win two seats in the [[4th Saeima]]. However, after the [[1934 Latvian coup d'état]] multi-party elections were not held again until [[Latvian Supreme Soviet election, 1990|1990]].
