{{ethnic group| |group=Lao Krang |image= |population=53,000 |popplace=[[Thailand]] |rels=[[Theravada Buddhism]] |langs=[[Lao language|Lao]], [[Thai language|Thai]] |related=[[Lao people|Lao]], [[Thai people|Thai]], other [[Tai peoples|Tai]] groups. }}
The '''Lao Krang''' ({{lang-th|ลาวครั่ง}}, {{RTGS|''Lao Khrang''}}, {{IPA-th|lāːw kʰrâŋ|pron}}; endonym: {{IPA-lo|laːw kʰaŋ|}}) are a sub-group of the [[Lao people|Lao]] [[ethnic group]]. Also known as the '''Tai Krang''' ({{lang-th|ไทครั่ง}}), they speak a dialect of the [[Lao language]] that is not too different from the modern Lao/Isan languages of Laos and [[Isan]]. The Lao Krang should not be confused with the Tai Khang (spelt the same as 'Thai Krang' in Thai) who are a closely related people inhabiting northeastern Laos.
==Geographic Location== The Lao Krang are spread out throughout Western and Central Thailand, especially the provinces of [[Phichit Province|Phichit]], [[Suphanburi Province|Suphanburi]], [[Uthai Thani Province|Uthai Thani]], [[Chai Nat Province|Chai Nat]], [[Phitsanulok Province|Phitsanulok]], [[Kamphaeng Phet Province|Kamphaeng Phet]], [[Nakhon Pathom Province|Nakhon Pathom]] and [[Nakhon Sawan Province|Nakhon Sawan]].
==History== The Lao Krang are descendants of Lao people from [[Luang Prabang Province|Luang Prabang]] and [[Houaphanh Province|Houaphanh]] provinces who were enslaved by invading [[Thai people|Siamese]] soldiers after the fall of the last remnant kingdoms of [[Lan Xang]]. The Lao Krang were settled in the rich farmlands of Central Thailand to work as farm labourers to increase food production for the army and capital. Aside from their geographic isolation, the cultural traits and language of the Lao Krang give away their ancestors' traditional homeland.
==Religion and Culture== The Lao Krang are [[Theravada|Theravada Buddhists]], but also maintain older [[Tai folk religion|animist beliefs]]. Especially revered is the tutelary spirit of the village, the ''hu chao nei''. Traditional activities include farming, as well as making a red dye from beetles used to stain textiles, hence the namesake ''krang'' or 'lac'. Traditionally, marriages were only between members of the same group.
